
sudo apt update && sudo apt install clamav clamav-daemon clamav-freshclam -y

sudo systemctl stop clamav-freshclam
sudo freshclam
sudo systemctl start clamav-freshclam

sudo clamscan -r -i --bell /mnt

Breakdown of the flags:
-r (Recursive): Scans all files and subfolders within /mnt.
-i (Infected): Only prints infected files to the terminal (otherwise, you'll see a wall of "OK" messages).
--bell: Plays a sound if a virus is found (handy if you're doing other things).
/mnt: The target directory.

If you want to automatically move infected files to a specific folder (safer than deleting) instead of just reporting them, you can use:
sudo clamscan -r -i --move=/path/to/quarantine /mnt

sudo crontab -e
0 3 * * 0 clamscan -r -i /mnt >> /var/log/clamav_mnt_scan.log 2>&1
0 3 * * 0 clamscan -r -i /mnt > /var/log/clamav/manual_scan_$(date +\%Y-\%m-\%d).log 2>&1
0 3 * * 0 (date; clamscan -r -i /mnt; echo "-------------------") >> /var/log/clamav/history_scan.log 2>&1

/var/log/clamav/clamav.log (Scanning via daemon)
/var/log/clamav/freshclam.log (Atualizações de assinaturas)

# Para ver apenas o que foi detectado de positivo no histórico:
grep "FOUND" /var/log/clamav/history_scan.log

TO DELETE: (CAREFULL)
0 0 * * * find /var/log/clamav/ -name "*.log" -mtime +15 -delete
